Strategies in the Life Writing of High-Ranking GDR Party Officials after the Wende -- t12: “Ein reines Phantasieprodukt” or “Hostile Biography”? Günter de Bruyn’s Vierzig Jahre and the Stasi files -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCombines an overview of academic approaches to "life writing" with case studies from crucial periods of twentieth-century German history.Life writing, a genre classification increasingly accepted among scholars of literature and other disciplines, encompasses not just autobiography and biography, but also memoirs, diaries, letters, and interviews. Whether produced as events unfolded or long after the event, all forms of life writing are attempts by individuals to make sense of their experiences. In many such texts, the authors reassess their lives against the background of a broader public debate about the past. This book of essays examines German life writing after major turning points in twentieth-century German history: the First World War, the Nazi era, the postwar division of Germany, and the collapse of socialism and German unification. The volume is distinctive because it combines an overview of academic approaches to the study of life writing with a set of German-language case studies. In this respect it goes further than existingstudies, which often present life-writing material without indicating how it might fit into our broader understanding of a particular culture or historical period. Contributors: Rebecca Braun, Magnus Brechtken, Holger Brohm, Birgit Dahlke, Pauline Eyre, Mary Fulbrook, Ute Hirsekorn, Sara Jones, J. J. Long, Anne Peiter, Joanne Sayner, Dennis Tate, Roger Woods. Birgit Dahlke is Professor of German Literature at the Leuphana University of Lüneburg, Germany; Dennis Tate is Emeritus Professor of German Studies at the University of Bath, UK; Roger Woods is Professor of German and a Pro-Vice-Chancellor of the University of Nottingham, UK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiographyxGerman authors. 0aGerman prose literaturexHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aLiterature and historyxHistoryy20th centuryzGermany. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAcademic approaches.  aBiography.  aCultural studies.  aDiaries.  aExperiences.  aGerman Life Writing.  aGerman unification.  aInterviews.  aLetters.  aMemoirs.  aNazi era.  aPostwar division.1 aBraun, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrechtken, Magnus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrohm, Holger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlke, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlke, Birgit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEyre, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulbrook, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsekorn, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, J. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeiter, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayner, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTate, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTate, Dennis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWoods, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoods, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is p